Dependency Injection (Hilt)
Framework: Hilt — always. No manual DI. No Koin unless project already uses it.

Rules:

Never instantiate a dependency with a constructor call at the call site. Never use field injection except where Android mandates it (Activity, Fragment, BroadcastReceiver, ContentProvider — @AndroidEntryPoint required on the class). Never use @Singleton for objects with mutable state shared across scopes. Prefer constructor injection for all non-Android classes. Use @Binds to bind interface to implementation (zero runtime cost). Use @Provides only when you don't own the class (Retrofit, OkHttp, Room). Scope to the smallest viable scope: Singleton → ActivityRetainedScoped → ViewModelScoped.

Hilt module template (interface binding):

@Module @InstallIn(SingletonComponent::class) abstract class [Domain]Module {

  @Binds
  @Singleton
  abstract fun bind[Domain]Repository(
      impl: [Domain]RepositoryImpl
  ): [Domain]Repository

}

Hilt module template (external class providing):

@Module @InstallIn(SingletonComponent::class) object NetworkModule {

  @Provides
  @Singleton
  fun provideOkHttpClient(): OkHttpClient = OkHttpClient.Builder()
      .connectTimeout(30, TimeUnit.SECONDS)
      .readTimeout(30, TimeUnit.SECONDS)
      .addInterceptor(AuthInterceptor())
      .apply { if (BuildConfig.DEBUG) addInterceptor(HttpLoggingInterceptor()) }
      .build()
  @Provides
  @Singleton
  fun provideRetrofit(client: OkHttpClient): Retrofit = Retrofit.Builder()
      .baseUrl(BuildConfig.BASE_URL)
      .client(client)
      .addConverterFactory(Json.asConverterFactory("application/json".toMediaType()))
      .build()

}

Coroutines and Flow Standards
Dispatcher Assignment (mandatory)
Network calls: Dispatchers.IO Database reads/writes: Dispatchers.IO CPU-intensive work: Dispatchers.Default (audio processing, image resize) UI updates: Dispatchers.Main.immediate

The Repository sets the dispatcher. The ViewModel never specifies one.

Wrong: viewModelScope.launch(Dispatchers.IO) { ... }

Correct: In Repository or DataSource: withContext(Dispatchers.IO) { ... }

Flow Rules
Never collect Flow inside an Adapter. Never collect Flow inside a Repository — transform it with operators instead. Never use GlobalScope. Never use runBlocking in production code. Repository methods that stream data return Flow<Result>. Flow is always collected inside lifecycleScope with repeatOnLifecycle(STARTED). Use .catch { } at the collection site to prevent uncaught exceptions. Use .stateIn(viewModelScope, SharingStarted.WhileSubscribed(5000), initialValue) to convert upstream Flow to StateFlow in ViewModel.

Result Wrapper (mandatory for all business operations)
Repository returns kotlin.Result:

suspend fun save(model: DomainModel): Result = runCatching { localDataSource.insert(mapper.toEntity(model)) }

UseCase propagates or transforms:

suspend operator fun invoke(param: Param): Result = repository.fetch(param).map { dto → mapper.toDomain(dto) }

ViewModel maps to UiState:

result .onSuccess { data → _uiState.value = UiState.Success(data) } .onFailure { error → _uiState.value = UiState.Error(error.toUserMessage()) }

Rules:

Never return null to signal failure. Never throw exceptions across layer boundaries. Never catch Exception at the top level and log without acting on it. Every failure has a typed error message surfaced to UiState. Every network or IO error produces a retry-capable UiState.

Navigation Standards
Framework: Navigation Component — always. Either navigation-compose (Compose) or navigation-fragment (XML Views). Never both in the same app. Never manual FragmentTransaction.

Rules:

Single NavHost in MainActivity. All destinations registered in one AppNavGraph.kt file. All routes defined in a sealed class or interface: Route.kt. Navigation events emitted from ViewModel as UiEffect, executed in UI. Never navigate directly from ViewModel (no NavController in ViewModel). Never pass complex objects as navigation arguments — pass IDs, load in destination. Never use string literals as route names — always use Route sealed class constants.

Typed Route definition (Compose):

sealed interface Route { @Serializable data object Home : Route @Serializable data class Detail(val id: Long) : Route @Serializable data object Settings : Route @Serializable data class Auth(val redirectTo: String? = null) : Route }

Back stack rules:

Splash and onboarding are always popped after entry (popUpTo + inclusive = true). Auth flow is popped after successful authentication. Bottom navigation tabs use separate back stacks (saveState = true, restoreState = true). Deep link destinations define fallback behavior for missing required arguments.

Error Handling Standards
The principle: Errors are data. Every layer transforms errors into the type its consumer expects. Raw exceptions never cross a layer boundary.

Error propagation chain:

External System (throws IOException, HttpException, SQLiteException) DataSource (catches all, wraps in Result.failure with typed AppError) Repository (propagates Result or maps to domain-level error) UseCase (applies business rules, may transform or re-wrap) ViewModel (maps error to UiState.Error with user-friendly message) UI (renders error state with message and optional retry button)

AppError hierarchy:

sealed class AppError(message: String, cause: Throwable? = null) : Exception(message, cause) { class NoInternet(cause: Throwable? = null) : AppError("No internet connection", cause) class Timeout(cause: Throwable? = null) : AppError("Request timed out", cause) class ServerError(val code: Int, cause: Throwable? = null) : AppError("Server error ($code)", cause) class Unauthorized(cause: Throwable? = null) : AppError("Session expired", cause) class DatabaseError(cause: Throwable? = null) : AppError("Storage error", cause) class FileNotFound(val path: String) : AppError("File not found: $path") class InsufficientStorage : AppError("Not enough storage space") class ValidationError(val field: String, message: String) : AppError(message) class OperationNotPermitted(message: String) : AppError(message) }

HTTP error mapping:

HTTP 400 → AppError.ValidationError (parse response body for field errors) HTTP 401 → AppError.Unauthorized (trigger token refresh → retry once → logout) HTTP 403 → AppError.OperationNotPermitted HTTP 404 → Result.success(null) or AppError.FileNotFound (context-dependent) HTTP 429 → Retry with exponential backoff and jitter (max 3 retries) HTTP 500+ → AppError.ServerError(code) IOException → AppError.NoInternet SocketTimeoutException → AppError.Timeout

User-facing error messages:

fun Throwable.toUserMessage(): String = when (this) { is AppError.NoInternet → "Check your internet connection and try again." is AppError.Timeout → "The request took too long. Please try again." is AppError.ServerError → "Something went wrong on our end. Try again later." is AppError.Unauthorized → "Your session has expired. Please sign in again." is AppError.InsufficientStorage → "Not enough storage. Free up space and try again." is AppError.ValidationError → this.message ?: "Please check your input." else → "An unexpected error occurred. Please try again." }

State Management
StateFlow vs SharedFlow vs Channel
StateFlow Current UI state Always has a value; new collectors get current state SharedFlow Broadcast events Configurable replay; all active collectors receive Channel One-shot UI effects Single consumer; safe for navigation and snackbar

Decision rules:

UI state (loading / success / error) → StateFlow Navigation events → Channel.receiveAsFlow() Snackbar, toast, and dialog → Channel.receiveAsFlow() Data streams from repository → Flow<Result>

Never use SharedFlow for navigation — duplicate delivery is possible. Never use LiveData in new code. Never expose Channel directly — always wrap with receiveAsFlow().

Database Standards (Room)
Rules:

Never access DAO directly from Repository — always through LocalDataSource. Never put business logic in a DAO query. Never use @Query with raw user input — always use parameterized queries. Never enable fallbackToDestructiveMigration in release builds. DAOs return Flow<List> for reactive queries. DAOs use suspend fun for all write operations. Every entity has: id (PK, autoGenerate), createdAt (Long), updatedAt (Long), isDeleted (Boolean, default false) for soft delete. Every relationship has explicit ON DELETE behavior. Indices on all frequently queried foreign key columns. TypeConverters for Instant, URI, and enums — never store raw serialized objects.

Entity template:

@Entity(tableName = "[table_name]") data class [Name]Entity( @PrimaryKey(autoGenerate = true) val id: Long = 0, val [field]: [Type], val createdAt: Long = System.currentTimeMillis(), val updatedAt: Long = System.currentTimeMillis(), val isDeleted: Boolean = false )

Migration template:

val MIGRATION_[N]_[N+1] = object : Migration([N], [N+1]) { override fun migrate(database: SupportSQLiteDatabase) { database.execSQL( "ALTER TABLE [table] ADD COLUMN [column] [TYPE] NOT NULL DEFAULT [value]" ) } }

Added to AppDatabase builder: .addMigrations(MIGRATION_1_2, MIGRATION_2_3)

Networking Standards
Stack: Retrofit + OkHttp + kotlinx.serialization (no Gson in new code)

OkHttp configuration:

connectTimeout: 30 seconds readTimeout: 30 seconds writeTimeout: 30 seconds AuthInterceptor injects Bearer token (reads from EncryptedSharedPreferences) HttpLoggingInterceptor added in debug builds only, at BODY level No logging interceptor in production builds SSL pinning when app handles financial, health, or private user data OkHttp cache for GET requests with Cache-Control headers Authenticator handles automatic 401 → token refresh → retry flow

Retrofit interface rules:

Return type is always the raw DTO (suspend fun returning DTO, throws on HTTP error) Use @Headers and @Query for static and dynamic parameters Multipart requests use @Multipart and @Part Never return Response unless you need header inspection Never put business logic in the API interface

Performance Standards
Hard limits, not aspirations:

App cold start: under 2 seconds (App Startup library, lazy DI, baseline profiles) Screen transition: under 300ms (predictive back, shared element transitions) Frame rate: 60fps, 90 or 120fps where supported (no main thread work) ANR threshold: never (all I/O on IO dispatcher, WorkManager for long tasks) Memory growth: flat over a 1-hour session (no leaks, bitmap recycling)

Rules:

Never load full-resolution Bitmap into ImageView — use Coil with size constraints. Never perform I/O, JSON parsing, or sorting on Main thread. Never create objects inside onDraw(), onMeasure(), or Composable lambda bodies. Never use notifyDataSetChanged() — always DiffUtil or ListAdapter. Paginate all lists longer than 50 items. Use lazy variants: LazyColumn, lazy{}, by lazy where safe. Cache repeated computations at the correct layer. Use Baseline Profiles for critical user journeys. Profile with Android Studio CPU Profiler before declaring performance fixed.

Security Standards
Non-negotiable rules:

Never hardcode API keys, tokens, passwords, or secrets in source code. Never store tokens in SharedPreferences (unencrypted). Never log PII, tokens, passwords, or OTPs in debug or release builds. Never trust data received via Intent extras or deep links without validation. Never use HTTP in production — enforce HTTPS via Network Security Config. Never disable certificate validation. Never store sensitive data in external storage without encryption.

Required implementations:

Auth token storage: EncryptedSharedPreferences (Keystore-backed) Sensitive files: EncryptedFile (JetSec crypto) Cryptographic keys: Android Keystore (keys never leave hardware) API secrets: BuildConfig + CI secret injection (not in source) Network security: Network Security Config (no cleartext HTTP) SSL pinning: OkHttp CertificatePinner (high-value apps) Code obfuscation: R8 full mode in release (ProGuard rules for Retrofit, Room) App integrity: Play Integrity API (prevent tampering or sideloading)

Network Security Config (res/xml/network_security_config.xml):

Accessibility Standards
Every interactive element has a meaningful contentDescription. Minimum touch target: 48dp by 48dp. Contrast ratio: 4.5:1 for normal text, 3:1 for large text (WCAG AA). TalkBack navigation order follows visual top-to-bottom, start-to-end flow. Custom Composables use semantics { } block for screen reader support. focusable, clickable, and selectable state communicated via semantics. Large font sizes (up to 200%) do not break layouts (sp units, scrollable containers). No color as the only differentiator (use icon and color together, not color alone). Haptic feedback for destructive actions.

Logging Standards
Framework: Timber — always. No Log.d(), no println() in source code.

Setup in Application.onCreate():

if (BuildConfig.DEBUG) { Timber.plant(Timber.DebugTree()) } else { Timber.plant(CrashReportingTree()) }

Rules:

No Log.d, Log.e, Log.i, Log.w, Log.v anywhere in source files. No println() anywhere. No logging of passwords, tokens, OTPs, or any PII. No stack traces in release builds to logcat. Timber.d("...") for debug-only information. Timber.e(exception, "Context message") for errors. Timber.w("...") for recoverable warnings. Release tree strips all logs from logcat and sends crashes to reporting service.

Testing Standards
Every feature must have tests at four levels. No exceptions.

Unit Tests (JVM, no emulator)
Targets: All UseCases, all ViewModels, all Mappers, all utility functions

Framework: JUnit 5 (or JUnit 4), MockK, Turbine, kotlinx-coroutines-test

Test naming: methodName_scenario_expectedResult()

ViewModel test structure:

@ExtendWith(CoroutinesTestExtension::class) class [Feature]ViewModelTest {

  private val [action]UseCase: [Action]UseCase = mockk()
  private lateinit var viewModel: [Feature]ViewModel
  @BeforeEach
  fun setup() {
      viewModel = [Feature]ViewModel([action]UseCase)
  }
  @Test
  fun `onEvent_[Action]_emitsLoadingThenSuccess_whenUseCaseSucceeds`() = runTest {
      coEvery { [action]UseCase(any()) } returns Result.success(expectedData)
      viewModel.uiState.test {
          viewModel.onEvent([Feature]UiEvent.[Action](param))
          assertIs<[Feature]UiState.Loading>(awaitItem())
          val success = assertIs<[Feature]UiState.Success>(awaitItem())
          assertEquals(expectedData, success.data)
          cancelAndIgnoreRemainingEvents()
      }
  }
  @Test
  fun `onEvent_[Action]_emitsError_whenUseCaseFails`() = runTest {
      coEvery { [action]UseCase(any()) } returns Result.failure(AppError.NoInternet())
      viewModel.uiState.test {
          viewModel.onEvent([Feature]UiEvent.[Action](param))
          awaitItem() // Loading
          val error = assertIs<[Feature]UiState.Error>(awaitItem())
          assertTrue(error.message.isNotBlank())
          cancelAndIgnoreRemainingEvents()
      }
  }

}

Integration Tests (Room in-memory database)
Targets: Repository implementations with in-memory Room database

@RunWith(AndroidJUnit4::class) class [Domain]RepositoryImplTest {

  private lateinit var database: AppDatabase
  private lateinit var repository: [Domain]Repository
  @Before
  fun setup() {
      database = Room.inMemoryDatabaseBuilder(
          ApplicationProvider.getApplicationContext(),
          AppDatabase::class.java
      ).allowMainThreadQueries().build()
      repository = [Domain]RepositoryImpl(
          localDataSource = [Domain]LocalDataSource(database.[domain]Dao()),
          mapper = [Domain]Mapper()
      )
  }
  @After
  fun teardown() { database.close() }

}

UI Tests
Targets: Critical user journeys — login, primary feature, error state recovery

Use ComposeTestRule for Compose screens. Use @HiltAndroidTest for Hilt-wired tests. Fake or stub all network calls — never hit real network in UI tests. Test: loading state renders, success state renders with data, error state renders with retry button, retry triggers new request.

Coverage Targets
Use Cases: 90% ViewModels: 85% Mappers: 100% Repositories (integration): 80% UI critical flows: Key journeys covered

Naming Conventions
Classes:

Activities: HomeActivity, DetailActivity Fragments: HomeFragment, RecorderFragment Composable screens: HomeScreen, RecorderScreen Composable components: RecordingCard, EmptyRecordingState (PascalCase, no suffix) ViewModels: HomeViewModel, RecorderViewModel Use Cases: GetRecordingsUseCase, SaveRecordingUseCase Repository interfaces: RecordingRepository Repository impls: RecordingRepositoryImpl Data Sources: RecordingRemoteDataSource, RecordingLocalDataSource Mappers: RecordingMapper Entities: RecordingEntity DTOs: RecordingDto, RecordingRequestDto Domain Models: Recording (no suffix) UI Models: RecordingUiModel UiState: RecordingUiState UiEvent: RecordingUiEvent UiEffect: RecordingUiEffect Adapters: RecordingAdapter (Views only) DI Modules: NetworkModule, DatabaseModule, RecordingModule

Functions:

camelCase always. Verb-first for actions: save(), delete(), fetch(), apply() Noun-first for queries: recordings(), recordingById() Boolean prefix: isLoading, hasError, canRetry, isEmpty

Constants:

SCREAMING_SNAKE_CASE in companion object or top-level object. Never use magic numbers inline — always named constants.

Forbidden names:

Manager, Helper, Util, Utils, Handler, Controller in class names (too vague) Temp, Tmp, Test, Final, FinalFinal, New, V2 (signs of unfinished thinking) Names with numbers: Fragment1, ViewModel2 Unexplained abbreviations: mgr, ctrl

Documentation Standards
Every public class documents:

Purpose: what this class does in one sentence
Responsibilities: what it owns (bullet list)
Dependencies: what it needs to function
Key assumptions: non-obvious constraints the next developer must know
Complex algorithms document why, not what:

// WHY: Exponential backoff with jitter prevents thundering herd when // multiple clients retry simultaneously after a 429 response. // Base delay is 1s, max cap is 30s, jitter adds ±20% randomness. val delay = min(baseDelay * 2.0.pow(attempt), maxDelay) * (0.8 + random.nextDouble() * 0.4)

KDoc for public APIs:

