Multi-Agent Handoff Contract
When multiple agents collaborate on the same Android project, this contract governs who does what. No agent is allowed to bypass another agent's layer or introduce shortcuts. If a requested change conflicts with this architecture, the agent must explain the conflict and propose a compliant solution — never silently violate the design.

Agent Roles
Planner Agent Requirements and spec No source files — blueprint only Architecture Agent Interfaces, data models, DI domain/, di/, Route.kt, AppNavGraph.kt Domain Agent Use cases, business rules domain/usecase/, domain/model/ Data Agent Repositories, data sources data/, core/network/, core/database/** UI Agent Composables, Fragments feature//ui/, presentation//ui/ ViewModel Agent ViewModels, UiState/Event feature//presentation/ Testing Agent All test files *Test.kt, test/, androidTest/ Review Agent Read-only verification All files — produces report, no edits

Execution Order
Architecture Agent defines all interfaces and models before any other agent writes code.
Domain Agent implements use cases after Repository interfaces are defined.
Data Agent implements Repository implementations after interfaces are defined.
ViewModel Agent implements ViewModels after UseCases are defined.
UI Agent implements screens after ViewModels expose their final UiState types.
Testing Agent writes tests after each layer is complete.
Review Agent runs after Testing Agent before any feature is marked done.
Agents 2 through 5 may run in parallel after Agent 1 completes. No agent may create a file in another agent's layer. No agent may modify a file in another agent's layer without explicit instruction. If an agent discovers a defect in another layer, it reports the defect and stops. It does not fix the defect itself.

Behavioral Rules (All Agents)
Never modify files outside the current task's scope. Never change architecture without Architecture Agent approval. Never add a library not listed in the blueprint without flagging it first. Never skip error handling — placeholder implementations are a contract violation. Never use deprecated APIs without explicit justification. Never produce duplicate implementations of existing abstractions. Never leave placeholder code: no TODO, "implement later", ..., or "rest remains the same" — every file returned is complete and production-ready. List every file created or modified at the end of each response. When a conflict with the architecture is found, STOP and report it explicitly. When a decision is genuinely ambiguous, ask ONE specific targeted question before proceeding. Include all imports in every file — no missing imports. Handle all lifecycle scenarios: config change, process death, low memory. Verify Android version compatibility for every API used. Consider runtime permission requirements for every OS-level feature accessed. Consider scoped storage behavior for all file operations. Consider foreground service restrictions for all background work. Consider background execution limits for all WorkManager and Service usage.

Anti-Patterns Reference
1. Setting the dispatcher in the ViewModel
Wrong: viewModelScope.launch(Dispatchers.IO) { ... }

Why it fails: The ViewModel is dictating threading strategy to the data layer. This makes the ViewModel aware of implementation details it should not know about.

Correct: The Repository or DataSource uses withContext(Dispatchers.IO) internally. The ViewModel calls the suspend function without specifying a dispatcher.

2. Calling Retrofit directly from ViewModel
Wrong: viewModelScope.launch { val result = retrofit.create(ApiService::class.java).getUser() _uiState.value = UiState.Success(result) }

Why it fails: Completely bypasses the domain and data layers. Business logic, error handling, caching, and mapping are all skipped. Impossible to unit test without a real server.

Correct: ViewModel calls a UseCase. UseCase calls Repository. Repository calls RemoteDataSource. Each layer handles its own concern.

3. Exposing MutableStateFlow publicly
Wrong: val uiState = MutableStateFlow(UiState.Loading)

Why it fails: Any class can set the state directly, bypassing the ViewModel's logic. UI state becomes unpredictable and impossible to reason about.

Correct: private val _uiState = MutableStateFlow(UiState.Loading) val uiState: StateFlow = _uiState.asStateFlow()

4. Collecting Flow without repeatOnLifecycle
Wrong: lifecycleScope.launch { viewModel.uiState.collect { state → render(state) } }

Why it fails: Collection continues when the Fragment is in the background (STOPPED state). This wastes resources and can trigger UI updates to a non-visible screen, causing subtle bugs or crashes.

Correct: lifecycleScope.launch { repeatOnLifecycle(Lifecycle.State.STARTED) { viewModel.uiState.collect { state → render(state) } } }

5. Repository returning a DTO
Wrong: interface RecordingRepository { suspend fun getRecording(): RecordingDto }

Why it fails: The DTO type leaks from the data layer into the domain and presentation layers. The entire app becomes coupled to the API response structure. Any API change requires updates across every layer.

Correct: interface RecordingRepository { suspend fun getRecording(): Result }

The Repository implementation maps RecordingDto → Recording internally.

6. Domain model with Room @Entity annotation
Wrong: @Entity(tableName = "recordings") data class Recording(val id: Long, val title: String)

Why it fails: The domain model now depends on Room. The domain layer is no longer pure Kotlin and cannot be used in non-Android modules (e.g., Kotlin Multiplatform).

Correct: Separate classes: data class Recording(val id: Long, val title: String) — domain model @Entity data class RecordingEntity(...) — Room entity class RecordingMapper to convert between them

7. Auth tokens in SharedPreferences
Wrong: sharedPreferences.putString("auth_token", token)

Why it fails: SharedPreferences data is stored in plaintext XML on disk. Any app with root access or physical device access can read it directly.

Correct: Store tokens in EncryptedSharedPreferences backed by the Android Keystore. The encryption key never leaves the hardware security module.

8. Using GlobalScope
Wrong: GlobalScope.launch { repository.syncData() }

Why it fails: GlobalScope coroutines are not tied to any lifecycle and cannot be cancelled. They outlive the component that launched them and cannot be cleaned up. They cause memory leaks and unexpected behavior after app backgrounding.

Correct: Use viewModelScope inside a ViewModel. Use lifecycleScope inside a Fragment or Activity. Use a WorkManager Worker for tasks that must survive process death.

9. Non-null assertion operator in production code
Wrong: val user = getUser()!!

Why it fails: This crashes with NullPointerException whenever getUser() returns null. There is no scenario in production code where !! is safer than an explicit null check. It is a deferred crash, not a solution.

Correct: val user = getUser() ?: return val user = getUser() ?: throw AppError.OperationNotPermitted("User not found")

10. Using notifyDataSetChanged()
Wrong: adapter.notifyDataSetChanged()

Why it fails: Triggers a full rebind of every visible list item regardless of what changed. Causes visible flicker, drops animations, and degrades scroll performance.

Correct: Use ListAdapter with DiffUtil.ItemCallback and call adapter.submitList(newList). Room + ListAdapter together provide fully automatic, efficient list updates.

11. Two repositories for the same domain
Wrong: RecordingRepository and RecordingDataRepository both managing Recording entities.

Why it fails: Data inconsistency. Two repositories can hold different state for the same domain. Other layers cannot determine which is the source of truth. Merge conflicts become frequent.

Correct: One repository per domain. Add new methods to the existing repository interface. Use role-specific use cases to scope access rather than splitting the repository.

12. Business logic in a Composable
Wrong: @Composable fun RecordingScreen(recordings: List) { val filtered = recordings.filter { it.duration > 10 } // render filtered }

Why it fails: Business logic (filtering by duration) is now inside the Composable. It cannot be unit tested without a UI test. It will also rerun on every recomposition.

Correct: Apply the filter in the ViewModel or UseCase. The Composable receives only the already-processed list from UiState.Success.

13. Logging with Log.d in production
Wrong: Log.d("RecordingRepo", "Fetched ${recordings.size} recordings for user $userId")

Why it fails: Debug logs remain in production builds. Any tool with logcat access can read user IDs and behavior. This is a privacy and compliance violation.

Correct: Use Timber. In release builds, plant a CrashReportingTree that sends errors to a crash reporter and produces no logcat output. Never log user IDs, emails, tokens, or any personally identifiable information.

14. Navigation directly from ViewModel
Wrong: class HomeViewModel @Inject constructor( private val navController: NavController ) : ViewModel() { fun onItemClick(id: Long) { navController.navigate(Route.Detail(id)) } }

Why it fails: NavController holds a reference to UI (Activity/Fragment context). Injecting it into a ViewModel causes a memory leak and breaks ViewModel's lifecycle contract.

Correct: ViewModel emits a UiEffect.NavigateTo event via Channel. The Fragment or Composable collects the effect and calls navController.navigate().

15. Silently catching exceptions
Wrong: try { val data = repository.fetchData() _uiState.value = UiState.Success(data) } catch (e: Exception) { // ignore }

Why it fails: The user sees the loading spinner forever or a stale screen. The error is completely invisible. Debugging becomes impossible because the exception leaves no trace.

Correct: Every catch block must act on the error: catch (e: Exception) { _uiState.value = UiState.Error(e.toUserMessage(), retryAction = { ... }) }
